## Normal Development Flow

The expected flow is:

1. Choose a track.
2. Inspect current worktree status.
3. Start or continue a run.
4. Make local code changes.
5. Sync changes to the remote validation server when needed.
6. Validate in the remote venv.
7. Record test evidence.
8. Prepare or review the image build plan.
9. Build an image only when the user asks.
10. Record image evidence.
11. Deploy only when the user asks.
12. Record deploy and deploy-verify evidence.

Do not run expensive build, deploy, publish, or remote mutation commands just
because they are available. Confirm intent from the user or the current run
context.

## Evidence Discipline

Runs under `.devteam/runs/` are the source of truth for what has been verified.

When a validation, build, publish, sync, deploy, or deploy-verify step is
performed, record evidence through devteam instead of only describing it in
chat.

Treat stale evidence carefully. If a worktree HEAD has changed after evidence
was recorded, start a fresh run for the current HEAD instead of appending new
evidence to the old run.

## Git Discipline

Do not revert user changes unless explicitly requested.

Before committing application code, inspect the relevant worktree:

```bash
git status --short
git diff --check
```

For devteam tool changes, also run the relevant devteam tests and skill lint.
For application repo changes, run the smallest meaningful validation first.

## Safety Rules

Do not run destructive git commands unless explicitly requested. Do not publish,
build, deploy, or mutate remote state without clear user intent.

When uncertain, open the dynamic workspace context, ask the user to choose the
track for the current session, then inspect the selected track context.
